GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 851
Short Title: Hospital Police Officer/Authority/Info Access. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Reeder, Miller, and Pyrtle (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Judiciary 2, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
April 10, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO TREAT HOSPITAL POLICE OFFICERS AS A DISTINCT CATEGORY OF
3 COMPANY POLICE OFFICERS AND TO PROVIDE CERTAIN AUTHORITY AND
4 INFORMATION ACCESS TO THESE OFFICERS.
5 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
6 SECTION 1. Chapter 74E of the General Statutes reads as rewritten:
7 "Chapter 74E.
8 "Company Police Act.
9 …
10 "§ 74E-6. Oaths, powers, and authority of company police officers.
11 …
12 (b) Categories. – The following three distinct classifications of company police officers
13 are established:
14 …
15 (1a) Hospital Police Officers. – Those company police officers who are employed
16 by a hospital as that term is defined under G.S. 131E-76(3).
17 …
18 (d1) Hospital Police. – Hospital police officers have the powers contained in subsection
19 (c) of this section and also have the powers in that subsection upon that portion of any public
20 road or highway passing through or immediately adjoining the property described in that
21 subsection, wherever located. The governing body of a hospital as defined by G.S. 131E-76(2)
22 may enter into a mutual aid agreement with the governing board of a municipality or, with the
23 consent of the county sheriff, a county to the same extent as a municipal police department
24 pursuant to Chapter 160A of the General Statutes.
25 …
26 (f1) Hospital Police CJLEADS Access. – Unless contrary to any federal law, regulation,
27 or requirement, a hospital police agency certified pursuant to this Chapter shall be granted access
28 to the Criminal Justice Law Enforcement Automated Data System (CJLEADS) upon (i) request
29 of the agency and (ii) compliance with the requirements established by the Government Data
30 Analytics Center (GDAC) for access to that system, including the execution of a license and
31 usage agreement.
32 (f2) Hospital Police DCIN Access. – Pursuant to all laws, rules, and regulations not
33 inconsistent with this subsection, hospital police agencies shall be granted access to and deemed
34 participating agencies of the Division of Criminal Information Network (DCIN) created under
*H851-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 G.S. 143B-905 in a manner equivalent, at a minimum, to campus police certified by the Attorney
2 General pursuant to Chapter 74G of the General Statutes.
3 …."
4 SECTION 2. G.S. 115D-5(b) reads as rewritten:
5 "(b) In order to make instruction as accessible as possible to all citizens, the teaching of
6 curricular courses and of noncurricular extension courses at convenient locations away from
7 institution campuses as well as on campuses is authorized and shall be encouraged. A pro rata
8 portion of the established regular tuition rate charged a full-time student shall be charged a
9 part-time student taking any curriculum course. In lieu of any tuition charge, the State Board of
10 Community Colleges shall establish a uniform registration fee, or a schedule of uniform
11 registration fees, to be charged students enrolling in extension courses for which instruction is
12 financed primarily from State funds. The State Board of Community Colleges may provide by
13 general and uniform regulations for waiver of tuition and registration fees for the following:
14 …
15 (2) Courses requested by the following entities that support the organizations'
16 training needs and are on a specialized course list approved by the State Board
17 of Community Colleges:
18 …
19 f. Municipal, county, or State law enforcement agencies.
20 f1. Campus police agencies of private institutions of higher education
21 certified by the Attorney General pursuant to Chapter 74G of the
22 General Statutes.
23 f2. Hospital police agencies certified by the Attorney General pursuant to
24 Chapter 74E of the General Statutes.
25 …."
26 SECTION 3. Notwithstanding any provision of law to the contrary, there shall be no
27 impediment to the use of the Voice Interoperability Plan for Emergency Responders (VIPER)
28 system by hospital police agencies certified by the Attorney General pursuant to Chapter 74E of
29 the General Statutes, so long as those agencies choose to acquire the necessary equipment and
30 utilize the VIPER system.
31 SECTION 4. This act is effective when it becomes law.
